qas.question: Aside from die casting, what are alloys of zinc mixed with copper, aluminium and magnesium used for?
Alloys of zinc mixed with copper, aluminium and magnesium are marketed as what?
What is possible to produce thanks to the low melting point and low viscosity of zinc aluminium alloy?
What brand name of alloy is supposed to be as strong as steel while still being malleable as plastic?
What is used to mold Prestal?

answers.text: die casts made of ceramics and cement.

qas.question: What are alloys of zinc mixed with copper, aluminium and plastic used for?
What is possible to produce thanks to the high melting point and high viscosity of zinc aluminium alloy?

plausible_answers.text: die casts made of ceramics and cement

qas.question: What is used to remove Prestal?
What are alloys of zinc mixed with steel and copper marketed as?
What brand name of alloy is supposed to be as strong as silk while still being malleable as butter?

context: Alloys of primarily zinc with small amounts of copper, aluminium, and magnesium are useful in die casting as well as <a0_0><b5_0>spin casting<b5_0/><a0_0/>, especially in the automotive, electrical, and hardware industries. These alloys are marketed under the name <a1_0><b8_0>Zamak<b8_0/><a1_0/>. An example of this is zinc aluminium. The low melting point together with the low viscosity of the alloy makes the production of <a2_0><b6_0>small and intricate shapes<b6_0/><a2_0/> possible. The low working temperature leads to rapid cooling of the cast products and therefore fast assembly is possible. Another alloy, marketed under the brand name <a3_0><b9_0>Prestal<b9_0/><a3_0/>, contains 78% zinc and 22% aluminium and is reported to be nearly as strong as steel but as malleable as plastic. This superplasticity of the alloy allows it to be molded using <a4_0><b7_0>die casts made of ceramics and cement<b7_0/>.
